  "prompt": "What's the difference between \u51e0 and \u591a\u5c11 in the following sentences?",
  "response": "When comparing the usage of \u51e0 (j\u01d0) and \u591a\u5c11 (du\u014dsh\u01ceo) in the context of asking about quantities, the key difference lies in the implied expectation of the answer.\n\n1. \u51e0 (j\u01d0):\n- \u51e0 is typically used when the expected answer is a smaller, countable number, usually less than 10. It is often used when you have a general expectation that the quantity is limited and manageable.\n- Example Sentence: \u4f60\u5bb6\u6709\u51e0\u4e2a\u623f\u95f4\uff1f (N\u01d0 ji\u0101 y\u01d2u j\u01d0 ge f\u00e1ngji\u0101n?)\n  Translation: How many rooms does your house have?\n- The expectation here is a small number of rooms, possibly less than 10.\n\n2. \u591a\u5c11 (du\u014dsh\u01ceo):\n- \u591a\u5c11 is used when the answer could be a larger number or when the quantity is not specifically limited to a small range. It can be used for both small and large numbers, providing a broader scope.\n- Example Sentence: \u4f60\u5bb6\u6709\u591a\u5c11\u623f\u95f4\uff1f (N\u01d0 ji\u0101 y\u01d2u du\u014dsh\u01ceo f\u00e1ngji\u0101n?)\n  Translation: How many rooms does your house have?\n- Here, there is no implication about the number of rooms being small; it could be a larger number as well.\n\nTo summarize, \u51e0 is for smaller, more countable quantities typically expected to be less than 10, while \u591a\u5c11 is used for asking about quantities that could vary widely and are not restricted to a small range.",
